				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: white scale<a name="47841"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 23 04 2:21 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Keep in mind that getting the white scale used to be just as frustrating.  True, we didn't have single groups farming the scale, but during that time, the scale was also used for a quest for one of the more desired caster cloaks in the game.  So, you would organize a Vox or Gore raid... a raid that at that time required large numbers of casters and many casters would demand equal rights for the scale or they wouldn't help.  Defaulting the scale usually resulted in few to no casters helping.
<br />

<br />
I do sympathize though with the plight of those trying to battle the people so bored that they have to farm trivial content to sell the items for money that they probably don't even need anymore.  I like the idea of a change similar to what was made with the cleric epic.  If you can, kill Gore or Vox for the chance at a scale.  If you can't, you can roam Skyfire trying to collect rare drop items to make a combine that, when handed in, would trigger a dragon (perhaps a tad tougher than Gore as Gore really is trivial these days) that would drop the scale and have fewer other drops.
<br />

<br />
Of course, I have long been a believer that an epic quest should test your abilities of your class... not your patience for the insanely boring.  Having to kill the same mob 20+ times because the drop rate is so incredibly crappy says nothing for how well you know your character.  All it says is that you had the endurance to lose a bunch of fun play time to continually track the same mob and kill him repeatedly.  After all, the original lore of the epics stated it was an item given to show you had become a true master of your class.  Much has changed though... with what the epics represent as well as so many other things.</span></td>
